SIMPLE: stuff
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stuff
<hw>Stuff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>estoffe</ets>,
F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧toffe</ets>; of uncertain origin, perhaps of Teutonic
origin and akin to E. <ets>stop</ets>, v.t. Cf. <er>Stuff</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Material which is to be worked up in
any process of manufacture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the <qex>stuff</qex> they had was sufficient for all the work
to make it, and too much.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxvi. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ambitions should be made of sterner <qex>stuff</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The workman on his <qex>stuff</qex> his skill doth show,⟦br⟧
And yet the <qex>stuff</qex> gives not the man his skill.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fundamental material of which anything is made
up; elemental part; essence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet do I hold it very <qex>stuff</qex> o' the conscience⟦br⟧
To do no contrived murder.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Woven material not made into garments; fabric of any
kind; specifically, any one of various fabrics of wool or worsted;
sometimes, worsted fiber.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>stuff</qex> wilt have a kirtle of?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It [the arras] was of <qex>stuff</qex> and silk mixed, though,
superior kinds were of silk exclusively.</q> <rj><qau>F. G.
Lee.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Furniture; goods; domestic vessels or
utensils.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He took away locks, and gave away the king's <qex>stuff</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A medicine or mixture; a potion.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Refuse or worthless matter; hence, also, foolish or
irrational language; nonsense; trash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Anger would indite⟦br⟧
Such woeful <qex>stuff</qex> as I or Shadwell write.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A melted mass of turpentine,
tallow, etc., with which the masts, sides, and bottom of a ship are
smeared for lubrication.</def> <rj><qau>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Paper stock ground ready for use.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ When partly ground, called <xex>half stuff</xex>.</note>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Clear stuff</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Clear</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Small stuff</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>all kinds of
small cordage.</cd> <au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au> -- <col><b>Stuff
gown</b></col>, <cd>the distinctive garb of a junior barrister; hence, a
junior barrister himself. See <altname>Silk gown</altname>, under
<er>Silk</er>.</cd></cs><-- <col><b>stuff and nonsense</b></col>. (See
def. 6 for stuff) <cd>balderdash, twaddle, nonsense, foolishness.</cd>
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stuff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stuff
<hw>Stuff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stuffed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stuffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>stoffen</ets>; cf. OF.
<ets>estoffer</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧toffer</ets>, to put stuff in, to
stuff, to line, also, OF. <ets>estouffer</ets> to stifle, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧touffer</ets>; both perhaps of Teutonic origin, and akin to
E. <ets>stop</ets>. Cf. <er>Stop</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Stuff</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fill by crowding something
into; to cram with something; to load to excess; <as>as, to
<ex>stuff</ex> a bedtick</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes this crook drew hazel bought adown,⟦br⟧
And <qex>stuffed</qex> her apron wide with nuts so brown.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest the gods, for sin,⟦br⟧
Should with a swelling dropsy <qex>stuff</qex> thy skin.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To thrust or crowd; to press; to pack.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Put roses into a glass with a narrow mouth, <qex>stuffing</qex>
them close together . . . and they retain smell and color.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fill by being pressed or packed into.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With inward arms the dire machine they load,⟦br⟧
And iron bowels <qex>stuff</qex> the dark abode.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>To fill with a seasoning
composition of bread, meat, condiments, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>stuff</ex>
a turkey</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To obstruct, as any of the organs; to affect with
some obstruction in the organs of sense or respiration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'm <qex>stuffed</qex>, cousin; I can not smell.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To fill the skin of, for the purpose of preserving
as a specimen; -- said of birds or other animals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To form or fashion by packing with the necessary
material.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An Eastern king put a judge to death for an iniquitous sentence,
and ordered his hide to be <qex>stuffed</qex> into a cushion, and placed
upon the tribunal.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To crowd with facts; to cram the mind of; sometimes,
to crowd or fill with false or idle tales or fancies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To put fraudulent votes into (a ballot box).</def>
<mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1430 --></p>

<p><ent>Stuff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stuff
<hw>Stuff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To feed gluttonously;
to cram.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Taught harmless man to cram and <qex>stuff</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stuffer</ent>⟦br⟧
